T1  - Kanban Controlled Pull Systems: An Analytic Approach
AU  - Deleersnyder, Jean-Luc
AU  - Hodgson, Thom J.
AU  - Muller-Malek, Henri
AU  - O'Grady, Peter J.
Y1  - 1989/09/01
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.35.9.1079
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.35.9.1079
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1079
EP  - 1091
VL  - 35
IS  - 9
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Three problem areas exist in designing and implementing a kanban controlled JIT system: the identification of flow lines problem, the flow line loading problem and the operational control problem. This paper addresses the operational control problem. A general N-stage serial production system is modeled as a discrete time Markov process. Capacity constraints, stochastic machine reliability and demand variability are included. The model is illustrated by a 3-stage system, describing the effects of the number of kanbans, the machine reliability, the demand variability and safety stock requirements on the performance of a kanban controlled pull system.
AB  - Three problem areas exist in designing and implementing a kanban controlled JIT system: the identification of flow lines problem, the flow line loading problem and the operational control problem. This paper addresses the operational control problem. A general N-stage serial production system is modeled as a discrete time Markov process. Capacity constraints, stochastic machine reliability and demand variability are included. The model is illustrated by a 3-stage system, describing the effects of the number of kanbans, the machine reliability, the demand variability and safety stock requirements on the performance of a kanban controlled pull system.
